ce:section.ce:para:
This study examined the photocatalytic degradation of MB dye using SS-CQDs, ZnO, and ZnO/SS-CQDs under UV–visible irradiation. The UV–Vis spectra (Fig. 8
                     ) illustrate the gradual reduction in the distinctive absorbance peak of MB at λ
                     max of 663 nm. The SS-CQDs exhibited a negligible reduction in absorbance (Fig. 8a), indicating a degradation efficiency of merely 16 % after 90 min, underscoring their constrained photocatalytic activity. The light-only condition (absence of catalyst) yielded only 2 % degradation, indicating minimal photolysis under UV light alone. A notable reduction in absorbance was observed for ZnO (Fig. 8b), resulting in a degradation efficiency of 35 %. This enhancement can be attributed to ZnO's potential to produce reactive oxygen species (ROS) through electron-hole pair excitation [51]. Nevertheless, the recombination of these carriers constrained its overall efficacy. The ZnO/SS-CQDs nanocomposite (Fig. 8c) exhibited the most significant decrease in absorbance, attaining an impressive degradation efficiency of 94 % in 90 min (Table S4). The enhanced performance arises from the synergistic interaction between ZnO and SS-CQDs, with SS-CQDs improving light absorption, promoting charge separation, and inhibiting recombination, thereby increasing the rate of ROS generation.
